# Secure Offline Premium & Encrypted Storage Implementation

Implement the offline auth algorithm from `offline_auth_algorithm.md` with AES-256-GCM encrypted localStorage and tamper-proof monotonic time tracking.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **No external dependencies are needed.** All cryptography (AES-GCM, RSA-OAEP, SHA-256) uses the browser's native `Web Crypto API` (`window.crypto.subtle`), which is hardware-accelerated, FIPS-compliant, and available in all modern browsers. Zero npm packages to install.

> [!WARNING]
> **RS256 Public/Private Key Pair:** Since we don't have a backend server yet (Supabase Edge Functions aren't set up), we will implement the full signature verification infrastructure but use a **simulated offline token** for now. When you deploy Supabase Edge Functions later, you simply plug in the real endpoint and it works. The frontend verification code is production-ready from day one.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **AES Encryption Scope:** All sensitive data stored in `localStorage` will be encrypted with AES-256-GCM before writing. This includes:
> - The Supabase auth token (`sb-*-auth-token`)
> - The Zustand auth store (`spirox-auth-storage`)
> - The offline premium token (`spirox_offline_token`)
> - The monotonic time tracker (`spirox_last_verified_time`)
> - User profile data (`spirox_user_name`, `spirox_user_avatar`, etc.)
> - Session/exercise data (`spirox_sessions`, `spirox_custom_exercises`, etc.)

## Proposed Changes

### Infrastructure Layer (`src/lib/`)

#### [NEW] [crypto.ts](file:///c:/Users/ajmal_inv2bct/OneDrive/Desktop/web%20projects/spirox/apps/web/src/lib/crypto.ts)
AES-256-GCM encryption/decryption utility using the native Web Crypto API.
- `deriveKey(passphrase)`: Derives a 256-bit AES key from a device-bound passphrase using PBKDF2.
- `encrypt(plaintext)`: Encrypts any string with AES-256-GCM, returns base64 ciphertext + IV.
- `decrypt(ciphertext)`: Decrypts AES-256-GCM ciphertext back to plaintext.
- The encryption key is derived from a combination of the Supabase project URL + a hardcoded app salt. This means the key is unique per deployment but consistent across page reloads.

#### [NEW] [secureStorage.ts](file:///c:/Users/ajmal_inv2bct/OneDrive/Desktop/web%20projects/spirox/apps/web/src/lib/secureStorage.ts)
Drop-in replacement for `localStorage.getItem`/`setItem` that transparently encrypts and decrypts.
- `SecureStorage.setItem(key, value)`: Encrypts `value` with AES-256-GCM, then stores it.
- `SecureStorage.getItem(key)`: Reads ciphertext, decrypts it, returns plaintext.
- `SecureStorage.removeItem(key)`: Standard removal.
- Graceful fallback: if decryption fails (corrupted/tampered data), returns `null` and removes the key.

#### [NEW] [offlineAuth.ts](file:///c:/Users/ajmal_inv2bct/OneDrive/Desktop/web%20projects/spirox/apps/web/src/lib/offlineAuth.ts)
Core offline premium verification engine implementing the algorithm from `offline_auth_algorithm.md`.
- `verifyOfflinePremium()`: The main verification function that runs the full flowchart:
  1. Check if offline token exists → if not, return `FREE`.
  2. Verify RSA signature on the token → if invalid, return `FREE`.
  3. Check monotonic time (current time >= last_verified_time) → if failed, return `FREE`.
  4. Check if current time < expiry_date → if expired, return `FREE`.
  5. Update `last_verified_time` → return `PREMIUM`.
- `storeOfflineToken(signedToken)`: Saves the server-signed offline token to encrypted storage.
- `clearOfflineToken()`: Removes the offline token (on logout/delete).
- Embeds the RSA **Public Key** for signature verification.

